How to make your SAS jobs run an order of magnitude faster

Hi Team

see attached utl_fasterjobs.sas

* I was asked to subset a 1.6 billion sas dataset
  for 6 hcpcs_cds for just March and April 2013
  No usefull indexes;

Timings for four methods

   1. 32 minutes for traditional method
   2. 8 minutes for the systask below( 6 concurrent jobs - could do more should be linear)
   3. ? minutes Modulo method not run. 6 minutes?
   4. 9 minutes using grid (6 concurrent jobs could easily run. Grid has more overhead?)

This is a very general method that applies to any SAS dataset
that is sorted. If the data is not sorted you can partition
the large dataset using mod(any large unique integer,x=0,1,2,3,4,5,6,7)=0
to process 8 mutually exclusive
partitions of the dataset. Both methods require that
you use a view to concatenate the result. Try  not
to materialize the concatenation, unless absolutely needed.
Sometimes that partitions are useful individually?

Methods 1 and 2 will run much faster on an inexpensive
windows/linux power workstation like the $600 Dell T7400's
off lease on EBAY or any more expensive Dell I7.
Need at least 8 cores and SPDE?

You can run jobs concurrently with the grid or if
you have access to the operating system you can use
systask as shown below.

Here is the 32 minute version

* first method 32 minutes;

data top_xxxxxxxxxxx;
     set xxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxx(
          where=(srvc_month in ('01APR2013'd,'01MAR2013'd) and
                     hcpcs_cd in (
                       '99211' '99212' '99213' '99214' '99215' '66984'))
          keep=
           xxx
           state_county_fips_prov
           xxxxxxxxxxx
           hcpcs_cd
           xxxxx
           srvc_month
           xxxxxx
           xxxxxxxx
           xxxxxx
           xxxxxx
          );
  run;quit;


* second method SYSTASK 8 minutes;

* find the first and last observation numbers for each month;
data breakpoint  (keep=month count first last);

   array firstobs {12};
   array lastobs  {12};

   firstobs{1}=1;
   lastobs{dim(lastobs)}=nrecs;

   do m=1 to dim(firstobs)-1;
      lastobs{M}=firstobs{M};
      firstobs{M+1}=nrecs;
     do while (lastobs{M}+1 ^= firstobs{M+1});
        p=floor((lastobs{M} + firstobs{M+1})/2);
        set xxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxx point=p nobs=nrecs;
            month=month(srvc_month);
        if month=m then lastobs{M}=p;
        else firstobs{M+1}=p;
     end;
   end;

   do month=1 to dim(firstobs);
     count=  lastobs{month}+1-firstobs{month};
     first=firstobs{month};
     last=lastobs{month};
     output;
   end;

   stop;
run;quit;

/*
NOTE: DATA statement used (Total process time):
      real time           0.16 seconds
      cpu time            0.14 seconds
*/

