Keep statement not the where statement that reduces processing time

see attached file sys_kep_where.sas

I suspect the keep statement and not the where statement
is responsible for reducing processing time, at least
when extracting a 10% sample of 3 variables from a big dataset.

This needs more vetting.

My benchmarks indicate equal timings(exactly?) for

set xxxxxxxx.xxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxx(keep=month member isu where=(mod(member,10)=0));

set xxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxx(keep=month member isu);
if mod(member,10)=0;

Full benchmark code is below.
Sorry I did not provide data.

This is important for parallel processing because it allows
partitioning of the input data. You CANNOT partition the input
with a where statement and the DOW loop does not work when using a
where statement. The DOW loop DOES support firstobs and
obs in both loops. This is also a big deal?

These two algorithms too exactly 27 seconds (26:51 and 26:88 seconds)
full code is below

Note modulus algorithms is an excellent means of partitioning input.

options lrecl=32756; * fixes trucation with cards in 9.3;
* mac var _o is autocall folder;
data _null_;file "&_o/sys_where_keep.sas";input;put _infile_;putlog _infile_;
cards4;
%macro sys_where_keep;
%utlopts;
data where;
  retain cnt 0;
  set xxxxxxxx.xxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxx(keep=month member isu where=(mod(member,10)=0));
  cnt+1;
  if cnt > 500000 then stop;
run;quit;
%mend sys_where_alone;
;;;;
run;quit;

options lrecl=32756; * fixes trucation with cards in 9.3;
* mac var _o is autocall folder;
data _null_;file "&_o/sys_keep_alone.sas";input;put _infile_;putlog _infile_;
cards4;
%macro sys_keep_alone;
options obs=10000000;
%utlopts;
data where;
  retain cnt 0;
  set xxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxx(keep=month member isu);
  if mod(member,10)=0;
  cnt+1;
  if cnt>500000 then stop;
run;quit;
%mend sys_keep_alone;
;;;;
run;quit;

systask kill xq1;systask command "&_s -termstmt %nrstr(%sys_where_keep;) -altlog &_r/log/sys_where_keep.log" taskname=xq1;
systask kill xq2;systask command "&_s -termstmt %nrstr(%sys_keep_alone;) -altlog &_r/log/sys_keep_alone.log" taskname=xq2;

