OPM has notified NTEU that the necessary regulations will be published for public comment by the end of May to add 13 new locality pay areas.

The Federal Salary Council (FSC) met on October 17, 2014, and the FSC once again recommended adding 12 new locality pay areas based on data from the Bureau of Labor Statistics (BLS) demonstrating that private sector pay in these areas far exceed the rates in the “Rest of U.S.” areas:

·         Albany-Schenectady-Amsterdam, NY Combined Statistical Area;
·         Albuquerque, NM Metropolitan Statistical Area;
·         Austin-Round Rock-Marble Falls, TX Combined Statistical Area;
·         Charlotte-Gastonia-Salisbury, NC-SC Combined Statistical Area;
·         Colorado Springs, CO Metropolitan Statistical Area;
·         Davenport-Moline-Rock Island, IA-IL Metropolitan Statistical Area;
·         Harrisburg-Carlisle-Lebanon, PA Combined Statistical Area;
·         Laredo, TX Metropolitan Statistical Area;
·         Las Vegas-Paradise-Pahrump, NV Combined Statistical Area;
·         Palm Bay-Melbourne-Titusville, FL Metropolitan Statistical Area;
·         St. Louis-St. Charles-Farmington, MO-IL Combined Statistical Area; and
·         Tucson, AZ Metropolitan Statistical Area.

These 12 areas have been included in the FSC’s recommendations for the last two years, but have not yet been acted upon.  Although the President’s Pay Agent gave tentative approval to adopt these new areas, no action was taken to publish the necessary regulations required to implement these new locality pay areas, presumably because the President’s Alternative Pay Plan did not provide any funding for locality pay increases.

The FSC also recommended, based on the BLS data, that Kansas City also be added as a separate locality pay area, NTEU also continued to recommend the expansion of many other existing locality pay areas to better reflect local labor markets based on available commuting data and changes to the boundaries of Metropolitan Statistical Areas, as defined by the Office of Management and Budget based on 2010 census data. 

The Office of Personnel Management has notified NTEU that the necessary regulations will be published for public comment by the end of May, 2015 to designate these 13 areas as new locality pay areas.

This should result in formal approval of these 13 new locality areas by year-end.  I will keep you updated once the regulations are published for public comment and as the public comment period on the regulations proceeds.

The remaining question will then be when funding is provided towards locality pay for future January pay adjustments.  NTEU’s efforts on that front will continue, of course, and I will keep you informed of any developments.

